{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504018"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2095"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2095"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.46,0.07,0.01,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68346"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"568"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1159"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28454"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents with a painful and swollen finger to the Emergency Department. Three days earlier she had pricked her right index finger on a rose thorn whilst gardening and did not think much of it at the time. However, over the last two days the finger has started to hurt and now the whole finger became painful and swollen. Her medical history includes atrial fibrillation for which she takes apixaban. On examination, the index finger is swollen and held slightly flexed. There is tenderness along the flexor aspect of her finger. There is significant pain on passive extension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral antibiotics and GP follow-up","Intravenous antibiotics and specialist referral","Analgesia and GP review","Arm elevation and rest","Oral antibiotics and specialist outpatients"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history of trauma on the finger with digital swelling would suggest a diagnosis of flexor tenosynovitis, the most likely source being bacteria from her prick on the rose thorn. Kanavel\u0027s signs include swelling over the affected tendon, tenderness over the affected tendon, pain on passive extension of the affected finger, and the affected finger being held in slight flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is a risk of tendon necrosis and deeper spread of infection. Hence, infectious flexor tenosynovitis requires immediate commencement of broad spectrum intravenous antibiotics and referral to orthopaedics for consideration of incision and drainage and/or surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a potentially serious infection and requires \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E. Discharging this patient with GP or outpatient follow-up without orthopaedic or plastics review is not appropriate as this patient may require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute tenosynovitis requires antibiotic treatment and prompt orthopaedic referral.","Kanavel\u0027s signs are key clinical indicators of infectious flexor tenosynovitis."],"references":["Chapman T, Ilyas AM. Pyogenic Flexor Tenosynovitis: Evaluation and Treatment Strategies. J Hand Surg Am. 2019 Nov;44(11):981-985. doi: 10.1016/j.jhsa.2019.04.011. Epub 2019 Jul 2. PMID: 31272698. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31272698/","Ray G, Sandean DP, Tall MA. Tenosynovitis. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544324/","Challoumas D, Ramasubbu R, Rooney E, Seymour-Jackson E, Putti A, Millar NL. Management of de Quervain Tenosynovitis: A Systematic Review and Network Meta-Analysis. JAMA Netw Open. 2023 Oct 2;6(10):e2337001. doi: 10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2023.37001. PMID: 37889490; PMCID: PMC10611995. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10611995/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68346"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T18:47:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:50:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":